At the comitia tribu-ta, all the people‚ whether resident or not, voted in their proper tribes (see B. 1. c. 43. n. 11.) individually3 here each man²s vote was equally effectua13 so that the patricians, even if they attended them (which some doubt), had little influence. They were held without the authority of the patriciam, and for the purpose of creating the inferior magistrates, such as tribunes of the people‚ aediles, quaestors, δια, also proconsuls, propraetors, &c.; electing certain priests, and holding trials. Their deerees were called plebiscita, which, after the year 306, (see B. 3. c. 55,) bound the whole Roman people. Before that they bound only the plebeians.
